Exercise 2 (20 points)

Calculating the lowest, highest, mean, median, as well as the 10th and 90th percentile of the flow rates yields:

  • the lowest flow was 0 m3/s
  • the 10thpercentile of flow was 1.3810^{-4} m3/s
  • The mean flow rate was 0.508 m3/s.
  • The median flow rate was 0.0461 m3/s.
  • The 90th percentile of flow rate was 0.924 m3/s.
  • the highest flow was 37.2 m3/s

It is quite interesting to observe that the median and mean values are different by 91%, with the mean flow rate being much higher. That is because the rare high flow rates are really many times higher than the baseflow and drive the average value up by a lot. An indication of that is illustrated by the the disproportion of the 10th percentile being 330 times lower than the median, while the 90th percentile of flow being 20 times higher than the median.

Exercise 3 (20 points)

Calculating and comparing the arithmetic average and medium concentrations for nitrate, TP, SRP, and TSS over the entire year of record. As of note, the reference values for agricultural watersheds are, respectively, 5 mg N/L, 0.3 mg P/L, 0.03 mg P/L, and 20 mg TSS/L. Compare your results to these reference values.

Calculating the concentrations for nitrate yields:

  • The mean concentration for nitrate was 9.72 mg N/L
  • The median concentration for nitrate was 10.9 mg N/L.

These values are very similar, which suggests that the nitrate concentrations are relatively well distributed around the median at Cuyahoga River. The value of 9.72 mg N/L for the mean nitrate concentration, being slightly higher than that of the median suggests that they is little occurrence of high nitrate concentration values that do not play a disproportionate effect on the average concentration. Both values are about half of the reference value of 5 mg N/L.

This may suggest two things:

  • the nutrient pressure in this watershed may be smaller than in other ones in the Midwest, and/or
  • the watershed is large enough that the nitrogen removal processes in streams are making an impact

Calculating the concentrations for total phosphorus yields:

  • mean concentration for total phosphorus: 0.25 mg P/L.
  • median concentration for total phosphorus: 0.21 mg P/L.

The reference value given for agricultural watersheds is 0.3 mg P/L. This value was probably a bit on the high side and a better value should have been 0.2 mgP/L. This corresponds very well to the one calculated for the Cuyahoga River. The median concentration is 20% lower, which suggests that high values, although relatively rare, are observed.

Calculating the concentrations for SRP or phosphate yields:

  • The mean concentration for soluble reactive phosphorus calculated using the initial data yields 0.16 mg P/L. Obviously, this is not possible, and corresponds to large negative values in the SRP original dataset. To get around this, one could remove these values from the dataset by using the code SRPcorr<-data$SRP; SRPcorr[SRPcorr<=0]=NA; mean(na.omit(SRPcorr)), where the first part saves the initial data into a SRPcorr. Then all the negative values are replaced by NA, which means Not Available. Finally, the mean is calculated omitting the NA values. Using the corrected values of SRP concentrations, the arithmetic average concentration for SRP yields 0.16 mg P/L. This value is 440% or just about twice higher than the reference one given above. That reference value should really have been 0.02 mg P/L. So the SRP average concentrations in the Cuyahoga River is very high for phosphate.
  • The median concentration for soluble reactive phosphorus 0.14 mg P/L. This is also high, and confirms that the high average is not only due to rare very high values.

Exercise 4 (20 points)

Plot the hydrograph and nitrate, TP, SRP, and TSS chemographs for the Chickasaw River at Franklin, OHio, over the first two weeks of March 2009. Using text, report whether the chemographs exhibit a concentration or a dilution effect.

The chemographs are plotted herein. Nitrate concentrations exhibit a concentration trough during flow peak, and we say that there is a dilution effect of the nitrate concentrations relative to flow. Phosphate seems to exhibit a similar dilution pattern, although the chemograph appears ânoisierâ. Reversely, TP and SS concentrations exhibit a concentration effect as the concentrations increase with the first flow peak, and somewhat to the secondary peak. Both concentrations exhibit two secondary concentration peaks on the 12th and 13th of March, likely related to secondary rainfall events. Indeed, for these dates, the hydrograph is in the falling limb but there seems to be slight bumps, which may be indicative of intense events, yet short having little effect on flow rates, but which evidently play a role on water quality.

Exercise 5 (10 points)

Plot the flow duration curve over the entire period of record using the log/log scale graph. Report the total flow volume that occurred in 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest flow.

For this exercise, it was possible to use code made available.

The flow duration curve plotted using the normal distribution probabilities interestingly shows two linear trends. The first one between 1% and 25% of occurrence, and from 50% and up. It is possible to read directly on the graph to answer the questions above, at the cost of a bit of uncertainty. Instead, it is possible to obtain exact estimates of the flow volume occurring in 2% of the time corresponding to the highest flow, which we will name W2% from the vector calculated to make the plot, and which code would be Wk=quantile(cumQSort,probs=seq(0.01,1,0.01))/tail(cumQSort,1).

As such the flow duration values for 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest flow were estimated to be:

  • W2% = 46%
  • W5% = 67%
  • W10% = 81%

The last value, suggests that about one third of the flow volume occurred in 10% of the time corresponding to the highest flows. In reality this is a rather small percentage compared to what could be observed in smaller flashier watersheds.

Exercise 6 (20 points)

Plot the load duration curve over the entire period of record using the log/log scale graph. Report the total load that occurred in 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest loads.

To answer the question here, the idea was to calculate cumulative loads for each of the four parameters, and then, plot them all together with flow to be able to compare them. Again, for this, it was possible to use this code made available.





For nitrate, the mass duration values for 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest loads were estimated to be:

  • L2%-NO3 = 41%
  • L5%-NO3 = 63%
  • L10%-NO3 = 80%

For Total Phosphorus, the mass duration values for 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest loads were estimated to be:

  • L2%-TP = 71%
  • L5%-TP = 86%
  • L10%-TP = 94%

For Suspended Solids, the mass duration values for 2%, 5%, and 10% of the time, corresponding to the highest loads were estimated to be:

  • L2%-SS = 85%
  • L5%-SS = 94%
  • L10%-SS = 98%



The nitrate and mass duration curves appear below that of the flow duration curve, while the TP and SS mass duration curves are located above. This does make sense as the former two exhibited a dilution effect, where the concentrations were lowest during flow peaks, and the latter two have a concentration effect during flow peaks. It is remarkable to observe that in 78% of the SS mass load occurs in only 5% of the time, corresponding to only 25% of the flow volume. In other words, the vast majority of the suspended solid load in this River occurs in a relatively very short amount of time, and corresponding to the highest flows. For water quality monitoring purposes, this is a very difficult thing to cope with. Indeed, it means that to have any chance to evaluate SS mass loads, one must monitor all the time and on a frequent basis.
